text: John Belushi, Chris Farley, John Candy, Gabriel Iglesias, Lavell Crawford, Ralphie May, Louie Anderson, just a few of the greatest male comedians ever to make us laugh...All of them "plus-sized" men.  I find some of the statements here somewhat sexist when compared to the same type of male comedians (we adore) in regards to her weight and her character's persona of being down and out, fed-up, and feeling crummy about her life.  Her character looks the part.  I think her weight is a mute point.  She's funny in this part.  I think many people will relate with her character.  As far as her character's persona, didn't most of us love John Belushi's Bluto in "National Lampoon's Animal House"?  His character was not exactly a clean cut one, but we wouldn't dream of changing it.  Yet this wonderful female actor/comedian is judged differently because she chooses to take this role as a somewhat female version of what many male actors have become famous for.  Some of Chris Farley's characters were very close to the role she is playing in this movie, but I've never seen any review or opinions that were negative because his character was fat, sweaty, dumb and un-groomed.  We loved those characters, but here, I see a double standard from some when it comes to a female playing the same kind of role.

text: I see a lot of comments saying: oh! You don't have a sense of humor, you don't know anything about movies, you don't like this one because the lead actor is obese.  Ok, let's put all that aside and say I do have a sense of humor (it's mine, yes, I believe I share it with some people, but it's subjective). Well my sense of humor tells me: reuse a joke a billion times and it's not funny anymore: now they put that quite long sequence (for a trailer) with said joke in it, to conclude said trailer. That tells me that's probably one of the funniest one in the whole movie (that's the case for many many trailers nowadays). That should give everyone a hint about the general quality of this comedy (because whatever you say it is, it really is sold as a comedy).
